---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="About - Togglebase"
  description="Togglebase is an open-source, developer-first feature flag platform built for fast-moving startups and engineering teams."
>
  <Header />
  <main class="pt-14 sm:pt-16">
    <section class="py-16 sm:py-20 md:py-28">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl w-full px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 xl:px-0">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400">
          About Togglebase
        </p>
        <h1 class="mt-4 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-zinc-900 dark:text-white sm:text-4xl">
          Built for teams that ship fast
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-4 text-base sm:text-lg text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
          Togglebase is a developer-first feature flag platform for startups and product teams that want to move quickly
          without breaking production. It gives you remote control over features, rollouts, and experiments so you can
          ship confidently.
        </p>

        <div class="mt-10 grid gap-8 sm:grid-cols-2">
          <div class="rounded-2xl border border-zinc-200 dark:border-zinc-700 bg-white dark:bg-zinc-900/70 p-6">
            <h2 class="text-sm font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">
              Why it exists
            </h2>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
              Many teams start with <span class="font-mono">if feature_enabled</span> checks sprinkled through code and a few
              environment variables. That works, until it doesn&apos;t-rollbacks are slow, flags are hard to track, and every
              change needs a deploy.
            </p>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
              Togglebase centralises those decisions so you can flip a flag, run a rollout, or turn off a risky feature without
              waking your on-call engineer.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="rounded-2xl border border-zinc-200 dark:border-zinc-700 bg-white dark:bg-zinc-900/70 p-6">
            <h2 class="text-sm font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">
              Designed for developers
            </h2>
            <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
              <li>• A clean API and Python SDK that fits into existing apps.</li>
              <li>• Environments for dev, staging, and production built in.</li>
              <li>• Percent rollouts and A/B testing without custom plumbing.</li>
              <li>• A dashboard to see and manage every flag in one place.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-10 rounded-2xl border border-zinc-200 dark:border-zinc-700 bg-zinc-50 dark:bg-zinc-900/60 p-6 sm:p-7">
          <h2 class="text-sm font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">
            Open source and startup-friendly
          </h2>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
            Togglebase is open source so you can inspect how it works, extend it, or contribute improvements. It&apos;s meant to be
            easy to adopt in a new side project and strong enough to support a growing product.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
            The goal is simple: give you all the power of battle-tested feature flags without the overhead of a full-blown
            internal platform team.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Layout>

